	<p class="cs709C557D"><span class="cs5E1DB61D">WEST virginia legislature</span></p><p class="cs1CE9D70E"><span class="csB0C9F1E0">2026 regular session</span></p><p class="cs709C557D"><span class="csC2FEE544">Introduced</span></p><p class="cs3E63B65"><span class="cs8498B7A6">Senate Bill 601</span></p><p class="csFF933113"><span class="csADC6E5DB">By Senator Garcia</span></p><p class="cs8BEF69CE"><span class="cs7B75DFFE">[Introduced January 27, 2026; referred<br/>to the Committee on Health and Human Resources; and then to the Committee on the Judiciary]</span></p><p class="cs29F66C3F"><span class="csEF05ACC">A BILL to amend the Code of West Virginia, 1931, as amended, by adding a new article, designated &sect;62-12A-1, &sect;62-12A-2, &sect;62-12A-3, &sect;62-12A-4, &sect;62-12A-5, &sect;62-12A-6, and &sect;62-12A-7, relating to authorizing medical parole for certain inmates in the custody of the Division of Corrections and Rehabilitation; defining terms; providing for petition for medical parole and process for completing and submitting petition; providing for review of petitions by superintendents of correctional institutions; providing for notice of medical parole to interested parties, for hearings, and for development of terms and conditions of release; setting requirements for commissioner&rsquo;s final decision on petitions; establishing process for reconsideration and review of decisions denying medical parole; establishing reporting requirements; and providing rule-making authority. </span></p><p class="cs63FD752D"><span class="cs93AB6E8B">Be it enacted by the Legislature of West Virginia:</span></p><h2 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="cs456817A0">Article 12A. MEDICAL PAROLE.</span></h2>
	<h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-1. Definitions.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">For purposes of this article:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) &quot;Geriatric&quot; means a person who is aged 55 or older; is experiencing a chronic infirmity, illness, or chronic debilitating disease that is related to aging; and who requires assistance with at least one necessary daily life function.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) &quot;Medical parole&quot; means a release on parole pursuant to the provisions of this article due to a terminal illness, medical incapacity, or geriatric condition.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) &quot;Medically incapacitated&quot; means that an individual requires assistance with at least one necessary daily life function because of a medical, cognitive, or mental health condition that is not expected to improve.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(d) &quot;Necessary daily life function&quot; means an essential self-care task including, but not limited to, breathing, bathing and showering, personal hygiene and grooming, dressing, toilet hygiene, functional mobility, and self-feeding.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(e) &quot;Terminal illness&quot; means a serious and advanced condition with an end-of-life trajectory, including, but not limited to, metastatic solid-tumor cancer, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), end-stage organ disease, and advanced dementia. A specific prognosis of life expectancy is not necessary for an inmate to be deemed to have a terminal illness.</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-2. Petition for medical parole.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) Any inmate incarcerated in a state correctional institution may petition for medical parole because of a terminal illness, medical incapacity, or geriatric condition.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) The superintendent of a state correctional institution shall consider an inmate for medical parole upon receipt of a written petition submitted by:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) The inmate;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) The inmate&rsquo;s legal counsel;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) The inmate&rsquo;s legal guardian or conservator;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) A family member acting on behalf of the inmate; or</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) Medical or correctional staff employed or contracted by the Division of Corrections and Rehabilitation.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) The division shall provide written medical parole petition forms online and in each correctional institution&rsquo;s law library and medical facility. Petition forms shall include, at a minimum, space for the petitioner to specify the reason for the medical parole request and the relevant medical diagnosis and prognosis, as well as space to submit a medical parole plan. The medical parole plan must be a written statement including:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) A written diagnosis accompanied by a signed affidavit on letterhead from a licensed physician, if not a medical provider utilized by the division;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) The proposed course of treatment for the inmate seeking medical parole;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) The proposed site for treatment and post-treatment care;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) Documentation that medical providers qualified to provide the medical services identified in the plan are prepared to provide such services;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) The financial plan in place to cover the cost of the proposed care for the duration of the medical parole; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(6) A release form signed by the inmate permitting copies of the medical parole petition and all supporting documents, including the medical parole plan, to be provided to and reviewed by medical staff at and the superintendent of the inmate&rsquo;s correctional institution, the Commissioner of the Division of Corrections and Rehabilitation or his or her designee, and the Parole Board. If the inmate is not competent to sign the release form, the inmate&rsquo;s legal or medical guardian shall sign the release form on the inmate&rsquo;s behalf.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(d) If the inmate or petitioner fails to submit a medical parole plan with the medical parole petition, the plan shall be developed by the superintendent of the state correctional institution in which the inmate is incarcerated within 30 days of submission of the petition, in consultation with a case manager assigned to the inmate for purposes of developing the medical parole plan. The absence of a medical parole plan from a medical parole petition shall not be a reason for the commissioner to deny medical parole under &sect;62-12A-5 of this code.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(e) Within 72 hours of any inmate&rsquo;s diagnosis of a terminal illness, medical staff at the inmate&rsquo;s correctional institution shall notify the inmate of the diagnosis. If an appropriate Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA) release form is on file for the inmate, medical staff shall also provide notice of the diagnosis to the inmate&rsquo;s legal counsel, legal guardian or conservator, and/or family member.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(f) Medical staff at each state correctional institution under the control of the division shall periodically review and consult with inmates possessing acute medical needs to determine whether they may satisfy the criteria for medical parole, and shall inform such inmates of the availability of the medical parole petition process.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(g) Any inmate may request assistance in obtaining and completing a medical parole petition, and relevant staff members at the inmate&rsquo;s correctional institution shall assist the inmate in completing and submitting the petition within 30 days of the inmate&rsquo;s initial request for assistance.</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-3. Review and recommendation by superintendent.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) Inmates shall submit all medical parole petitions to the superintendent of the correctional institution in which the inmate is incarcerated. A petition submitted to any other division employee or office shall be forwarded by the recipient to the appropriate superintendent for processing and review.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) The superintendent shall review each medical parole petition and, in consultation with the correctional institution&rsquo;s medical staff, confirm the relevant diagnosis of a petitioner asserting a terminal illness or medical incapacity or the medical conditions of a petitioner asserting a geriatric condition, as the case may be. Following such confirmation, the superintendent shall prepare a report summarizing the inmate&rsquo;s institutional history, rehabilitative or educational programming, evidence or lack of evidence of violence in the institutional setting, and other indicia of a risk of violence that the inmate poses to society, as demonstrated by the inmate&rsquo;s present medical condition and evidence-based factors.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Following review of the medical parole petition, the superintendent shall make a recommendation as to the release of the inmate on medical parole. Whether or not the superintendent recommends in favor of medical parole, the superintendent shall forward the recommendation, petition, and all supporting documents to the commissioner within 15 days of receipt of the petition for petitioners asserting a terminal illness or medical incapacity, and within 30 days of receipt of the petition for petitioners asserting a geriatric condition.</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-4. Notice by commissioner; hearing; terms and conditions of release.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) Upon receipt of a medical parole petition, supporting documents, and the recommendation of the superintendent, the commissioner shall notify the following individuals that the inmate is being considered for medical parole:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) The prosecuting attorney for the county in which the inmate was prosecuted and sentenced;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) The inmate;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) The person who petitioned for medical parole, if not the inmate; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) If applicable, the victim of the offense or a victim&rsquo;s family member or other adult individual that the victim requested be notified prior to or at the time of any release of the inmate.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) The commissioner shall provide the notice required by subsection (a) of this section telephonically or in writing. Notice to a victim or other person requested by the victim to be notified shall be provided to the last known address or addresses or telephone number or numbers provided by the victim or other person to be notified. If notification by telephone is attempted, notification is not complete unless it is given directly to the person requesting notification and after that person&rsquo;s identity has been verified.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) Any individual who receives notice under subsection (a) of this section may provide a written statement to the commissioner in support of or in opposition to the inmate&rsquo;s medical parole petition. Written statements must be provided to the commissioner on or before the deadline for the commissioner&rsquo;s final decision.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(d) The commissioner, in his or her discretion, may conduct a hearing on the medical parole petition. The commissioner shall determine who may attend the hearing; attendees may include, but are not limited to:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) The inmate;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) The person who petitioned for medical parole, if not the inmate;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) The inmate&rsquo;s or petitioner&rsquo;s legal counsel;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) The prosecuting attorney for the county in which the inmate was prosecuted and sentenced;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) If applicable, the victim or victim&rsquo;s family members;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(6) Division staff deemed necessary by the commissioner; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(7) A representative of the Parole Board.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(e) Any hearing held under subsection (d) of this section shall be closed to the public. The commissioner, or his or her designee, shall preside over every phase of the hearing and may impose procedural requirements such as time limits on oral testimony. The commissioner shall not be bound by the West Virginia rules of evidence in conducting the hearing. The commissioner may ask questions, and any person giving oral testimony shall testify under oath. The hearing shall be recorded in a manner to allow a written transcript of the proceedings to be produced if necessary.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(f) Following review of the medical parole petition and following any hearing held under subsection (d) of this section, if it appears to the commissioner that a decision to release the inmate on medical parole is likely, the commissioner shall investigate and determine the suitability of the proposed place of residence and course of treatment set forth in the petition&rsquo;s medical parole plan. The commissioner may, in his or her discretion, additionally consult with the Parole Board in developing appropriate terms and conditions of release for the medical parole.</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<a name="_Hlk219127706"><span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-5</span></a><span class="csF3C8A5A3">. Commissioner&rsquo;s final decision; reconsideration and review.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) The commissioner shall issue a final, written decision on the medical parole petition no later than 30 days after receipt of the recommendation of the superintendent. The commissioner shall consider the following factors in making a decision, with no single factor to be treated as being dispositive:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) The inmate&rsquo;s diagnosis, as confirmed by the superintendent, and likelihood of recovery;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) The approximate cost of providing health care to the inmate that would result to the division if the inmate were to remain incarcerated;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) The impact that the inmate&rsquo;s continued incarceration may have on the provision of medical care by the division generally and within the inmate&rsquo;s correctional institution specifically;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) The inmate&rsquo;s present likelihood of and ability to pose substantial danger to the physical safety of a specifically identifiable person or persons;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) Whether the inmate&rsquo;s medical condition was explicitly disclosed to the original sentencing judge or taken into account at the time of sentencing, and, if so, what if any changes have occurred to the inmate&rsquo;s health; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(6) Any written statements in support of or in opposition to the medical parole petition submitted in accordance with &sect;62-12A-4(c) of this code.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(b) The commissioner&rsquo;s decision shall be accompanied by a written statement of reasons supporting the decision as well as a statement of all conditions that must be met prior to the inmate&rsquo;s release.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(c) (1) An inmate who is denied medical parole may petition for reconsideration and review no sooner than six months following the date of the commissioner&rsquo;s decision denying parole. Any such petition for reconsideration and review must specify material changes to the inmate&rsquo;s medical condition(s) that have occurred since the time of the prior petition&rsquo;s submission. The commissioner shall deny any petition for reconsideration and review that lacks a statement of such material changes.</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) When the commissioner denies any medical parole petition, the commissioner shall, at the time of denial, notify the inmate of the month and year he or she may submit a petition for reconsideration and review. The commissioner shall, at least once every three years, reconsider and review the case of every inmate who was denied medical parole and who is still eligible.</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-6. Reporting.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(a) The commissioner shall, not later than December 1 of each year, make an annual report available on the division&rsquo;s website detailing, for the prior year:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(1) The number of medical parole petitions received;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(2) The number of petitions approved, the number denied, and the number of applicants, if any, that died while awaiting a decision;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(3) The average number of days that elapsed from the initial submission of medical parole petitions to the commissioner&rsquo;s final decision on each;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(4) The cost savings realized by the division as a result of no longer providing health care to inmates released on medical parole;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(5) By each inmate who was either granted or denied medical parole:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(A) Demographic data (including the inmate&rsquo;s race, ethnicity, gender, age, and correctional institution);</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(B) Source of the medical parole petition;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(C) A basic description of the underlying medical condition(s);</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(D) The highest class of offense for the inmate;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(E) The amount of time the inmate has been or was incarcerated;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(F) The reasons supporting the decision on the medical parole petition;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(G) A basic description of the medical setting of release; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(H) Whether the inmate, if granted medical parole, died after being granted parole but prior to being released from custody; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(6) The number of inmates approved for medical parole but whose release was delayed by more than one month, and for each such inmate:</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(A) Demographic data (including the inmate&rsquo;s race, ethnicity, gender, age, and correctional institution);</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(B) The reason for the delay;</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(C) Whether the inmate remains incarcerated as of the date of the annual report; and</span></p><p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">(D) A basic description of the underlying medical condition(s).</span></p><h4 class="cs89687900">
		<span class="csF3C8A5A3">&sect;62-12A-7. Rulemaking.</span></h4>
	<p class="cs53FB8D75"><span class="cs46AE26E6">The commissioner may propose rules for legislative approval in accordance with the provisions of &sect;29A-3-1 </span><span class="cs1489E706">et seq.</span><span class="cs46AE26E6"> of this code in implementing the provisions of this article.</span></p><p class="cs637BA255"><span class="cs7FA9C667">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="cs637BA255"><span class="cs7FA9C667">NOTE: The purpose of this bill is to establish a medical parole program for eligible inmates in the custody of the Division of Corrections and Rehabilitation. The bill provides for medical parole petitions to be submitted by inmates and provides for a review process by superintendents of correctional institutions and the commissioner of corrections and rehabilitation. The bill provides for notice of possible medical parole to interested parties, for hearings on parole petitions, and for development of terms and conditions of release. The bill sets a process for reconsideration and review of denials of medical parole, sets reporting requirements, and includes rulemaking authority.</span></p><p class="cs637BA255"><span class="cs7FA9C667">Strike-throughs indicate language that would be stricken from a heading or the present law and underscoring indicates new language that would be added.</span></p>


